					<div class="commentheading">On April 30, 2009 at 01:05 AM, tk121 (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>For a bit more vanilla flavor...</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">A great addition to this recipe is to add real vanilla bean into the custard just before pouring it into the ramikans.<br />
<br />
You can buy whole vanilla bean at most regular stores near the other spices, and it will look like a chile pepper.<br />
<br />
What you want to do is cut it in half along it's length over the custard, and scrape the inside of the bean causing the vanilla seeds in the center to go into the custard.  I typically let it sit for a little bit to allow the custard mixture to soak up some of the vanilla flavor before cooking in the oven.<br />
<br />
This will add a distinctive "vanilla" look to the custard with all the little seeds in it once it's cooked, and does wonders to the taste!  Very easy addition to the recipe, albeit a bit on the expensive side - 2 whole vanilla beans usually cost about 5 bucks.</div>
