					<hr size="1" noshade />
				
					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On August 13, 2009 at 04:42 AM, Michael Chu said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Re: creme brulee</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody"><div class='commentquote'>glow wrote:<div class='commentquotebody'>After being refrigerated to cool, my creme brulee developed a top layer that tastes like hardened butter; not a desirable addition. When removed, the rest of the custard was perfect. How can I avoid this from forming?</div></div><br />
Cover each ramekin with plastic wrap and make sure the plastic goes down onto the surface. That will help.<br />
<br />
<div class='commentquote'>glow wrote:<div class='commentquotebody'>Also, if the ramekins are glass, and the custard has been chilled, won't they break when put under a broiler or when they are torched to get the sugar crackle on top?</div></div><br />
I wouldn't put them under the broiler. Use a torch and keep moving - if you do it with constant motion, the glass should hold.</div>
